## 🔑 Tricks Learned

**Trick 1 — Only start from sequence beginnings**
```python
if (num - 1) not in num_set:
```
A number with no left neighbour in the set is the true start of a sequence. Skipping everything else means each sequence is only walked once, turning O(n²) into O(n).

**Trick 2 — Iterate over `num_set`, not `nums`**
```python
for num in num_set:   # not: for num in nums
```
Iterating the set automatically deduplicates. If `nums = [1, 1, 2]`, iterating `nums` would process `1` twice and potentially double-count. Iterating the set avoids this for free.

**Trick 3 — Hash set lookup is O(1), not O(n)**
The inner `while current in num_set` looks expensive but each lookup is O(1). The total number of lookups across the entire outer loop is O(n) — each element is a lookup target at most once per sequence it belongs to.

**Trick 4 — The outer loop can use `num_set` instead of `nums`**
Both work, but `num_set` is safer (no duplicates) and slightly faster in practice. The start-check `if (num - 1) not in num_set` handles the rest.

**Trick 5 — Edge case: empty array**
`set([])` is an empty set — the `for` loop simply doesn't execute and `longest = 0` is returned. No special case needed.

---

## The 5-Question Framework

| Question | Answer here |
|---|---|
| What do I **track**? | `num_set` (all values), `streak` (current run length), `longest` (best seen) |
| When do I **keep going**? | `while current in num_set` — as long as the next consecutive number exists |
| What happens **each step**? | Increment `current` and `streak`; update `longest` after each sequence finishes |
| What are the **edge cases**? | Empty array, all duplicates (`[1,1,1]` → 1), single element, negative numbers |
| What do I **return**? | `longest` — the length of the best sequence found |

---

## Aha Moment

The brute force re-walks every sequence from every starting point. The only fix needed is to identify where a sequence truly begins — a number with no left neighbour. That one `if (num - 1) not in num_set` check is the entire difference between O(n²) and O(n). The rest of the code is identical.

